---
import BaseLayout from '~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { apps } from '~/data/apps.generated';

// Apps currently using distributed-narrative methodology
const dnApps = apps.filter(a => a.distributedNarrative);

// Cases planned (Wave-1 retrofits — handoff docs shipped, asset gen pending)
const wave1Cases = [
  { slug: 'quillspell', name: 'QuillSpell', cast: '12-character cast — 6 etyma family archetypes (Latin/Greek/Old English/Norse/Norman-French/Arabic) + 6 spelling-pattern archetypes (silent letters, double consonants, schwa, vowel teams, suffixes, syllable rhythm)', status: 'Retrofit handoff shipped' },
  { slug: 'grammarforge', name: 'GrammarForge', cast: '12-character sentence-citizen cast — Mayor Subject, Verb Verity, Object Otto, Modifier Mike/Madge, Connector Chen, Pronoun Perry, Article Anne, Preposition Pat, Clause-Chief Carla, Punctuator Polly, Agreement Ada', status: 'Retrofit handoff shipped' },
  { slug: 'logicquest', name: 'LogicQuest', cast: '16-character cast — 12 fallacy archetypes (Ad Hominem Hannibal, Strawman Stella, Slippery-Slope Sam, etc.) + 4 valid-form heroes (Modus-Ponens Mo, Modus-Tollens Tara, Syllogism Solon, Disjunctive-Syllogism Dior)', status: 'Retrofit handoff shipped' },
  { slug: 'geometryforge', name: 'GeometryForge', cast: '10-character theorem-master cast — Master Pythagoras, Lady Inscribed-Angle, Sir Thales, Apprentice Heron, Axia + Theora (twins), Captain Construction, Compass Wraith, Madame Polygon, Master Tangent', status: 'Retrofit handoff shipped' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Our Method — Distributed-Narrative Learning"
  description="Distributed-narrative methodology — characters that embody the curriculum across kits. Spark & Anvil's pedagogical approach grounded in narrative-mode cognition and intrinsic-integration game design."
>
  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 pt-16 pb-8">
    <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-forge font-bold mb-3">Our method</p>
    <h1 class="font-brand font-bold text-4xl md:text-5xl text-anvil mb-6">
      Distributed-Narrative Learning
    </h1>
    <p class="text-xl text-anvil/70 leading-relaxed">
      Characters that don&apos;t just decorate the lesson — they <em>are</em> the lesson.
      Across a Spark &amp; Anvil app, a small cast of recurring named characters each embodies
      a specific curricular pattern: a chess tactic, a logical fallacy, a geometric theorem,
      a spelling rule. Kids learn the abstract pattern by following the character&apos;s story.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 pb-12">
    <div class="bg-forge/5 border-l-4 border-forge rounded p-6">
      <p class="text-anvil/80 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>Example.</strong> In GambitTales, our narrative-driven chess app, <strong>Sir Pinwell</strong>
        isn&apos;t just a character who teaches kids about pins. Sir Pinwell <em>is</em> the pin
        — every appearance demonstrates the pattern in a chess scenario. Across 16 kits of content,
        kids meet Sir Pinwell repeatedly in different positions. They learn the abstract concept
        through the recurring figure who embodies it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-anvil/5 py-16">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <h2 class="font-brand font-bold text-2xl text-anvil mb-6">The pedagogical foundations</h2>
      <p class="text-anvil/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Distributed-narrative methodology stitches together four well-attested cognitive and
        motivational moves from educational research:
      </p>
      <ul class="space-y-4 text-anvil/80 leading-relaxed">
        <li>
          <strong>Bruner&apos;s narrative-mode cognition</strong> (1986).
          Humans have two modes of thought — paradigmatic (logical-categorical) and narrative
          (story-as-meaning-making). Both serve learning, but formal subjects default to paradigmatic
          and become more accessible when bridged through narrative. Character archetypes engage
          narrative-mode encoding alongside paradigmatic content.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Sfard&apos;s participation metaphor</strong> (1998; revisited 2025).
          Learning is sometimes a commodity to acquire and sometimes a practice to participate in.
          When &quot;Sir Pinwell IS the pin tactic,&quot; kids don&apos;t acquire-a-fact-about-pins
          — they <em>participate</em> in a community of practitioners (real and fictional) who
          deploy the pattern.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Green &amp; Brock&apos;s narrative transportation</strong> (2000; updated 2024).
          When readers are absorbed into a narrative — focused attention, emotional engagement,
          mental imagery — they retain more, change attitudes more, and counter-argue less.
          Stable recurring characters maximize empathy + identification, the strongest single
          predictor of transportation.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Habgood&apos;s intrinsic-integration critique</strong> (2005).
          Endogenous fantasy (story-maps-to-content) was once hypothesized to be intrinsically
          motivating. Habgood reframed it: the fantasy/content fit must operate at the
          <em>mechanics</em> layer, not the surface layer. Distributed-narrative methodology takes
          this seriously — characters embody the mechanic, not just the decoration.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Pedagogical-agent meta-analyses</strong> (2021–2025).
          Multimedia-learning research on on-screen characters consistently shows small-to-moderate
          gains: retention g ≈ 0.20–0.39, transfer g ≈ 0.31, motivation g ≈ 0.26 — provided the
          character has affective cues, gestures, and a clear instructional role. We design every
          cast member to satisfy those conditions.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-16">
    <h2 class="font-brand font-bold text-2xl text-anvil mb-6">Where we use it today</h2>
    <p class="text-anvil/80 leading-relaxed mb-6">
      Our <strong>Narrative cluster</strong> is the first wave of apps built distributed-narrative
      from the ground up. Each app uses a stable cast where character behavior embodies a tactical
      or curricular pattern across all 16 kits of content.
    </p>
    <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
      {dnApps.map(app => (
        <a href={`/apps/${app.slug}`} class="block p-4 rounded-xl border border-anvil/15 hover:border-forge hover:shadow-md transition-all">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
            <span class="font-brand font-bold text-anvil">{app.name}</span>
            {app.mentor && <span class="text-xs text-anvil/60">• {app.mentor}</span>}
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-anvil/70 leading-relaxed line-clamp-3">{app.tagline}</p>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-anvil/5 py-16">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <h2 class="font-brand font-bold text-2xl text-anvil mb-6">Where we&apos;re extending it next</h2>
      <p class="text-anvil/80 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Wave-1 retrofits formalize a 12-to-16-character cast for each of four flagship apps.
        Cast designs are shipped via implementation handoff docs (in each app&apos;s repo);
        character art and per-kit integration follow.
      </p>
      <ul class="space-y-5">
        {wave1Cases.map(c => (
          <li class="border-l-4 border-forge/30 pl-5">
            <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-1">
              <a href={`/apps/${c.slug}`} class="font-brand font-bold text-lg text-anvil hover:text-forge">{c.name}</a>
              <span class="text-xs text-anvil/50 italic">{c.status}</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-sm text-anvil/70 leading-relaxed">{c.cast}</p>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-16">
    <h2 class="font-brand font-bold text-2xl text-anvil mb-4">Where we don&apos;t use it</h2>
    <p class="text-anvil/80 leading-relaxed mb-3">
      Distributed-narrative methodology isn&apos;t a universal solvent. Creative-tool and sandbox
      apps — BeatForge (music composition), SpectrumCanvas (visual art), PixelForge (pixel art),
      SoundSphere (soundscape design), SynaForge (synesthesia tool) — stay open-ended.
      Imposing a recurring cast on those apps would constrain kids&apos; creative agency in
      exactly the place where agency is the point.
    </p>
    <p class="text-anvil/80 leading-relaxed">
      We also design carefully against six known failure modes documented in our internal research
      — cast-size creep, surface-skinning, cultural bias, twee tone, curriculum lock-in, and
      intra-portfolio character collision. A registry of every named character across the
      portfolio prevents the last one.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="bg-spark/10 py-16">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 text-center">
      <h2 class="font-brand font-bold text-2xl text-anvil mb-3">For educators + researchers</h2>
      <p class="text-anvil/80 leading-relaxed">
        We&apos;re happy to share the research synthesis, per-app cast specs, and failure-mode
        design notes with educators, curriculum designers, and learning-science researchers.
        Email <a href="mailto:educators@spark-and-anvil.com" class="text-forge-text underline">educators@spark-and-anvil.com</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
